Itâ€™s the go-to refrain for Democrats watching Joe Biden fall behind Donald Trump in polls: Just wait until Trump is convicted. Yes, Bidenâ€™s historically unpopular. Yes, views of his job performance are growing increasingly negative. But if a jury of Trumpâ€™s peers in Manhattan, or South Florida, or Atlanta or Washington convicts him before Election Day, they say, it would have a dramatic impact on the race. Theyâ€™re probably wrong. The evidence so far suggests the race might shift only slightly, by a few points. That could be important in another close election, but itâ€™s not the kind of Trump collapse that Democrats may hope for â€” or Biden may need if his numbers donâ€™t improve. Trumpâ€™s legal peril is unprecedented, and the sentiment that a criminal conviction could be a mortal wound to his candidacy is mostly driven by political intuition right now. But weâ€™re starting to get more data on how a conviction would affect Trumpâ€™s chances to defeat Biden, thanks to pollsters whoâ€™ve asked voters what they would do if a jury found Trump guilty. Take last weekâ€™s Wall Street Journal poll. Trump led Biden by 4 percentage points in a head-to-head matchup, 47 percent to 43 percent. The race shifted only slightly, to a 1-point Biden lead, among respondents who were also asked what they would do if Trump were convicted in either of the two federal cases, either for unlawfully possessing classified documents or conspiring to overturn the results of the 2020 election. Since only about half of the respondents were asked about a hypothetical Trump conviction, the two results arenâ€™t directly comparable. But they suggest a massive swing against Trump is unlikely. And the margins are small: With just a 1-point lead in a hypothetical Trump conviction scenario, Democrats canâ€™t rely on a small post-conviction swing tipping the race. And thatâ€™s if heâ€™s even convicted before the election. Though Trumpâ€™s 2024 calendar is littered with planned trial dates up and down the Eastern Seaboard, thereâ€™s no guarantee that those cases wonâ€™t be pushed until after Election Day. The 2024 tea-leaf reading wouldnâ€™t be the first time that Trumpâ€™s controversies have led critics to prematurely bury his electoral prospects, whether it was the October 2016 revelation of the â€œAccess Hollywoodâ€ tape or predictions that the GOP would move on from the then-president in the wake of his 2020 defeat and the Jan. 6, 2021 riot at the Capitol. Of course, Trumpâ€™s poll numbers did drop â€” temporarily â€” following those events. But he recovered in time to defeat Hillary Clinton less than a month after the â€œAccess Hollywoodâ€ tape became public and, earlier this year, to become the prohibitive Republican favorite for the nomination. Last monthâ€™s New York Times/Siena College poll asked likely voters in six Biden-won swing states who said they werenâ€™t supporting him â€” a collection of Trump voters and those who said they were undecided â€” what they would do if Trump â€œwere convicted and sentenced to prison but were still the Republican nominee.â€ Most of them would still vote for Trump, but 5 percent of the likely electorate across those swing states said they would vote for Biden under that circumstance. Thatâ€™s potentially enough to tilt the race to the Democratic incumbent â€” but itâ€™s not guaranteed, especially with Biden already trailing. Most of that 5-point shift came from voters who were undecided or preferred another candidate in the initial Biden-Trump contest. The New York Times/Siena crosstabs also suggest young voters and independents who hadnâ€™t picked Biden before were slightly more likely to say they would vote for him if Trump were convicted. Other polls have similarly found that movement away from Trump in the event of a criminal conviction could provide a much-needed boost to Biden â€” but only a modest one. Half of respondents in a Vanderbilt University poll in Tennessee this month were asked to consider a straight matchup between Biden, Trump and Robert F. Kennedy Jr.; Trump led by 19 points.

The toy stores are bustling, inviting. Games and puzzles in boxes with lids. I'd love to buy every last one of them, but we never had any kids...       So baby I think I'll wrap myself up, pretty paper to be pulled apart. And wait for you to untie the bow, and unwrap my aching heart. Burn Out. Sometimes all it takes is a small change in thinking, or spelling in this case, to reframe a tough experience into something way way more powerful. I wrote this song last year after a series of events, both personal and professional, had left me in a bad state of burnout.Â  When I originally started writing this song, I was driven by the feeling to protest what I was experiencing. Protest the underlying culture that pushes so many of us to such a place. We're forced to keep on giving, and in return, we're rewarded with war after war, relentless climate change, poverty, and so many more awful things. While the rich keep on getting richer; today income inequality is the highest it's been since World War II. Some of the protest is maintained in the song (via a spoken word section in the second half), but I ultimately decided thereâ€™s more power in changing my way of thinking. I could choose whether to be a victim of burnout. Or I could choose to set an example of how I think we should treat one another. To Burn Out. I recognize Iâ€™m not always perfect at this, but at least I can set that as my intention every day. If we all came together with this intention, maybe we could set the world in a better direction. If any of this resonates with you, Iâ€™d be honored if you give it a listen. Let me know what you think! video_description: Durness is located in one of the most remote areas of mainland Scotland, way up in the far northwest corner of the country, close to Cape Wrath. Itâ€™s an area of unspoiled natural beauty, with miles of rugged coastline, vast tracts of barren moorland and isolated pockets of beautiful sandy beaches. If you have been on the North Coast 500, we lie right on this famous route 77 miles North of Dornoch; with the closest main airport south east of us at Inverness. If your idea of finding a links golf course involves an adventure, remoteness, turquoise ocean & sandy beaches then Durness GC could well be the golf experience you have been looking for. Designed by three local golf enthusiasts â€“ Lachie Ross, Ian Morrison and Francis Keith â€“ and opened in 1988, Durness Golf Club nestles on Scotlandâ€™s north coast and is Britainâ€™s most north westerly golf course on the mainland. We are a 9 hole links, but with a second set of tees that provides a fine 18 hole experience, set against some of the most stunning landscape backdrops you will see in the golfing world. Itâ€™s in this spectacular setting that the golf course at Durness Golf Club is set and itâ€™s recognised as one of the true hidden gems of Scottish golf, featuring on many a â€œmust playâ€ list of golfers whoâ€™ve read about the beguiling attractions of this little 9-hole links layout. The 6th/15th is the only par five on the card and itâ€™s a wonderful long hole, sweeping right around Loch Lanlish to the green. Fabulous though this hole undoubtedly is, the par three 9th /18th hole trumps it somewhat, as it calls for a tee shot to be played across a sea inlet to a small sand-protected green on the other side.#golf #scotland #uk #golfholiday #golfvacation #travel #travelblogger #egtgolftour #saturday

video_description: Imperfect beauty is actually perfect after all.  As you scroll through your beautifully curated feed filled with magazine-worthy Christmas decor and inspiration, I hope you remember your why and your who.  Who is your Christmas decor for? Why are you doing that craft? Is it for the people in your home to enjoy or for a perfect photo? And if that perfect photo happens with the sacrifice of othersâ€™ happiness, is it worth it? In yearsâ€™ past, we decorated early and I took my time styling every little corner of our home for Christmas. This year, weâ€™ve been so busy and had other projects happening, that the house is mostly still undecorated.  And Iâ€™ve felt like a failureâ€¦ but then I ask myself, â€œA failure to whom? To my kids or to my own expectations?â€ We as moms put so much pressure on ourselves to make everything perfect for the holidaysâ€¦ but maybe some of that pressure is our own self sabotage.  So hereâ€™s your sign to let go.  To breathe.  To release your expectationsâ€¦  because I promise you our families will still love us and enjoy this season as long as we just show up, imperfections and all. Our time and our energy is worth more poured into our people than poured into the pressure of social media perfection. Fill that tree with popsicle stick ornaments made by tiny hands.  Leave the dishes in the sink to go look at Christmas lights in the car in your pajamas.  Have fewer gifts wrapped under the tree by giving the gift of your time instead.  This season deserves your own peace just as much as everyone elseâ€™s. âœŒğŸ»#christmas

video_description: My Bro Scott Choppin Real Estate Development 101 Land JV Concept and Structures From day one of starting our real estate development company, weâ€™ve been making offers to landowners to participate with us on land joint ventures. Iâ€™ve had 99% of our offers declined, but the one percent that did accept were well worth the process. This post is to briefly delineate the concept and give you a couple different possible structures for you to make offers for your own projects. Generally, a land joint venture is a structure where the existing landowner conveys their land into a new partnership or LLC, and in return, is given a percentage ownership in that new LLC. You as the developer formulating and organizing the land JV, also get LLC membership shares The way we structure, land ventures is to attribute value to the land, which in essence is totally negotiable, within the context of whatâ€™s acceptable to a construction lender. Often, the land value is based on a recent appraisal, which also helps the conversation with the construction lenders on that land value. You as the developer, bring skillset, knowledge, capabilities, and capacity to develop the project, which often includes organizing the entire deal structure and project. This particularly means arranging lending and often including providing whatever guarantees are needed by the construction lender. This also includes specifically: strategy, entitlements, underwriting, permitting, construction, leasing, etc. The land joint venture partner is going to be most often a passive investor, One consideration - at least in the deals that we undertake - in a land structure, the land value is rarely enough equity to finance the whole project. So youâ€™re left with an equity gap that needs to be filled with additional equity, where we most often negotiate this as part of the JV, where the cash comes from the land JV partner as well. You can certainly raise third-party equity capital, and is a slightly more complicated structure.  One thing to know: Generally this land transfer into the new LLC will be a non-taxable event, as well as any development value uplift, as well as any permanent refinance cash out. The structures you can consider: 1. Build and sell 2. Build and hold 3. Build and exchange 4. Build and buy out the land JV partner. 5. Build and be bought out by the land JV partner To close, land JVâ€™s can be a very creative way to capture land opportunities, and obtain passive equity investments via land transfer.

A pile of laundry  has been waiting on your bed since this morning, and you pause to quickly turn  into an absolute folding machine. A meeting brings you to the end of the workday, which means it's time for Trader Joe's chicken fried rice, and catching a dub in chess while that's cooking. You devour the fried rice  and hop on for a Facetime with Megan, because long distance aka her living a mile and a half away from you  is tough during the week. Bakers as always need some attention, so you play with him as you debrief with Trevor, who's back from work. The gym is up next, the place you seldom get to  during the week nowadays with school, for some much needed chest and tris  and a little incline walk on the treadmill. You receive a kind note from your father in the mail, and hop on the line with your mother to catch up  before your MBA class. Afterwards you are back to petting Baker  and watching your roommate crumble into second place in Fortnite. Your gopuff has finally arrived, which is coming in clutch for your late night craving for sugar as you watch Thursday Night Football. Another day of living the dream.

voice_to_text: Big news from Capitol Hill today. Congress has just put a new rule on the books, and it's all about keeping the US firmly in NATO's corner. Here's the deal. From now on, any president thinking about pulling out of NATO will need a thumbs up from the Senate or an act of Congress. This move, championed by Senators Tim Kane and Marco Rubio, is part of the National Defence Authorization Act. And guess what? It's looking like President Biden's gonna sign off on it. Why this sudden focus on NATO? Well, remember the days when former President Trump had NATO on edge with his criticisms? Fast forward to now, and it's a whole new ball game under President Biden, especially with all that's going down in Ukraine. Senators Cain and Rubio are making it clear NATO's not just a club. It's a cornerstone of US security and a big old stop sign to authoritarian regimes. But it's not just talk. President Biden's been beefing up troops in Europe and working to get countries like Finland and Sweden on board with NATO. And with Trump eyeing a 2024 comeback, this new law is Congress's way of saying NATO's here to stay.

Joy Angela DeGruy (born October 16, 1957) is an American author, academic, and researcher, who previously served as assistant professor at the Portland State University School of Social Work. She is currently president and CEO of DeGruy Publications, Inc. She is most known for her book Post Traumatic Slave Syndrome, originally published by UpTone Press in 2005 and revised and republished in 2017 by JDP Inc. DeGruy and her research projects have featured in news and activist coverage of contemporary African-American social issues, in addition to public lectures and workshops on U.S. college campuses that include: Morehouse School of Medicine, Fisk University, Spelman College, Harvard University, Yale University, Princeton University, Smith College, Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). Dr DeGruy has spoken at the United Nations, UNESCO, C-SPAN, Oxford University, Association of Black Psychologists, National Association of Social Workers, the World Bank, The Essence Festival, and featured in Essence Magazine, and films that include: "Cracking the Codes" a film by Shakti Butler (World Trust Organization),"InVisible Portraits"by Oge Egbuonu on the Oprah Winfrey Network (OWN), among others. Dr. Degruy has also received a 2021 grant from the MacArthur Foundation to further her healing work. #blackhistory #blackhistory365 #americanhistory #blackhistoryisworldhistory #caribbean #indeginous #blackwoman #posttraumaticslavesyndrome #slavery#culturevulture #blacktiktok #joydegruy

video_description: George Santos has a new side hustle: selling custom video messages on the app Cameo. And unlike some of the former congressmanâ€™s previous financial pursuits, this is a perfectly legal and ethical gig, according to experts. After the New York Republican was expelled from the House earlier this month, Santos turned his talents to Cameo, an app that allows users to purchase personal videos made by public figures. Santos, who is facing 23 charges for wire fraud, identity theft, money laundering and other crimes, claimed to CBS that he made more money on the app in one week than he did after nearly a year in Congress with a $174,000 salary. Santosâ€™ videos, currently $500 a pop (the price has increased over time), have prompted a mixture of delight and mockery. Late night host Jimmy Kimmel pranked Santos into recording several videos for his show, and Sen. John Fetterman (D-Pa.) purchased one to troll scandal-plagued Sen. Bob Menendez (D-N.J.). â€œHe has a First Amendment right to make whatever videos he wants. And I think the public is going to take these videos in context, given his reputation and his conduct, but heâ€™s no longer subject to U.S. House ethics rules,â€ said Richard Painter, who served as chief White House ethics lawyer in the George W. Bush administration. Santos isnâ€™t a congressman anymore and has every right to profit off the videos, said Kathleen Clark, a professor of law who studies government ethics at Washington University in St. Louis. She pointed out that Cameo customers know where their money is going, â€œunlike those campaign donors who didnâ€™t know that he was going to be scaling their credit card numbers or appropriating campaign dollars for personal purposes.â€ Santos isnâ€™t the first politician who tried to profit off his troubles with the law, Painter said. Former President Donald Trump has been selling NFTs since last December, and he recently announced that snippets of the suit he wore for his August mug shot would be available for purchase. The New York Republican also isnâ€™t the first former politician to make money off Cameo: Rudy Giuliani and Sarah Palin have both made videos on the app in recent years. Richard Briffault, a professor of law who studies government ethics at Columbia Law School, suspects that users buy the videos based on Santosâ€™ amusement value rather than his connection to the crimes heâ€™s allegedly committed. â€œPeople want to pay for sort of silly things when people misbehave. Thereâ€™s not much you can do about it,â€ Briffaut said. #georgesantos

video_description: The "corrupt bargain" refers to the controversial presidential election of 1824. In that election, Andrew Jackson won the popular vote, but no candidate received a majority of the electoral votes. As a result, the decision went to the House of Representatives. Henry Clay, who was Speaker of the House at the time, used his influence to support John Quincy Adams, who eventually won the presidency. It was believed by many that Clay made a deal with Adams, promising his support in exchange for the position of Secretary of State. This arrangement was seen as corrupt because it seemed to undermine the will of the people who had voted for Jackson. So, the "corrupt bargain" refers to the alleged deal between Clay and Adams that led to Adams becoming president and Jackson losing the election. #APUSH #apush #apushmemes
